</EFX_FINANCIAL_DATA>
<EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<A NAME="FIS_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
<A NAME="D323345DS1A_HTM_ROM323345_15">
</A>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	CONDITION AND RESULTS OF OPERATIONS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	The following discussion and analysis of our financial condition and results of operations should be read together with &#147;Summary
	Historical Consolidated Financial Data,&#148; &#147;Selected Historical Consolidated Financial Data,&#148; and our historical audited and unaudited interim consolidated financial statements and related notes contained elsewhere in this prospectus.
	In addition to historical consolidated financial information, this discussion contains forward-looking statements that reflect our plans, estimates, and beliefs and involve numerous risks and uncertainties, including but not limited to those
	described in the &#147;Risk Factors&#148; section of this prospectus. Actual results may differ materially from those contained in any forward-looking statements. Factors that could cause or contribute to these differences include those discussed
	below and elsewhere in this prospectus, particularly in &#147;Risk Factors.&#148;
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Overview
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	With net sales of $23&nbsp;billion in the fiscal year ended January 2016, we are the second largest foodservice distributor in the United
	States with a 2015 market share of approximately 9%. The U.S. foodservice distribution industry is large, fragmented, and growing, with total industry sales of $268&nbsp;billion in 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Foodservice distribution is a competitive and fragmented industry, with over 15,000 foodservice distributors of various types and sizes of
	distributors serving the food-away-from-home market. In addition, there is competitive pressure from cash and carry retail stores, and club stores and new market entrants.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our mission is to be First in Food. We strive to inspire and empower chefs and foodservice operators to bring great food experiences to
	consumers. This mission is supported by our strategy of Great Food. Made Easy. This strategy centers on providing a broad and innovative offering of high-quality products to our customers, as well as a comprehensive suite of industry-leading
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	e-commerce,
</FONT>
	technology, and business solutions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We have significant scale and an efficient operating
	model. We supply approximately 250,000 customer locations nationwide. These customer locations include independently owned single and multi-unit restaurants, regional restaurant concepts, national restaurant chains, hospitals, nursing homes, hotels
	and motels, country clubs, government and military organizations, colleges and universities, and retail locations. We provide over 400,000 fresh, frozen, and dry food stock-keeping units, or SKUs, as well as
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-food
</FONT>
	items, sourced from over 5,000 suppliers. Our more than 4,000 sales associates manage customer relationships at local, regional, and national levels. They are supported by sophisticated marketing and
	category management capabilities, as well as a sales support team that includes world-class chefs and restaurant operations consultants. Our extensive network of 60 distribution centers and fleet of approximately 6,000 trucks allow us to operate
	efficiently and provide high levels of customer service.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Termination of Sysco Acquisition Agreement
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In December 2013, we entered into the Acquisition Agreement. Following the failure to obtain regulatory approvals, the Acquisition Agreement
	was subsequently terminated on June&nbsp;26, 2015. This
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	18-month
</FONT>
	period was challenging for our business. Sales growth slowed as many potential new customers were hesitant to switch their business to us during
	this period of uncertainty. During this time, we remained focused on our strategy by bringing innovative products to market, expanding our portfolio of business solutions for our customers, and driving advancements in technology. As it became
	apparent that obtaining regulatory approval would be more challenging than expected, we began to see a recovery of sales momentum, particularly with our independent restaurant customers. Following the termination of the Acquisition Agreement, this
	momentum has continued to build.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	51
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage59"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D323345DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
</EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<EFX_BUSINESS>
<A NAME="FIS_BUSINESS"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Business Drivers, Trends and Outlook
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our results for the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended October&nbsp;1, 2016 reflect steady execution of our growth strategy
	as evidenced by case volume growth, improving profitability and strategic acquisitions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Case volume growth of 2.5% during the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended October&nbsp;1, 2016 versus the comparable prior year period was driven by approximately 6.5% growth with independent restaurant customers and included growth across most customer categories. Net
	sales growth was impacted by significant deflation in the period, particularly in beef and dairy categories.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Product deflation also has a
	negative impact on gross profit dollars. These deflationary pressures were offset by favorable customer mix, acquisitions, and merchandising initiatives. Gross profit increased $91&nbsp;million for the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended October&nbsp;1, 2016 versus the comparable prior year period. As a percentage of net sales gross profit was 17.6%, up from 17.1% in the comparable prior year period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Efficiency and cost initiatives supported lower distribution, selling and administrative expenses. During the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended October&nbsp;1, 2016, these expenses declined $27&nbsp;million versus the comparable prior year period. In addition, restructuring and tangible asset impairment charges were $43&nbsp;million
	lower in the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended October&nbsp;1, 2016 versus the comparable prior year period. These actions reflect continued focus on ensuring we have a cost efficient and effective organization model. We closed
	our Baltimore, Maryland distribution center in the second quarter of 2016, and transferred the volume to lower cost facilities. We have substantially completed our field reorganization, which enables us to more efficiently manage multiple
	distribution centers from a hub and region structure. We have taken actions to begin centralizing certain field procurement activities in furtherance of our overall centralization efforts. We expect to complete these actions during 2017 and realize
	benefits in product costs and logistics resulting from more effective management of procurement and replenishment initiatives. In October 2016, we launched a corporate and administrative cost reduction program that will focus on streamlining the
	organization, through creating greater spans of control and expanded use of business shared services. We expect to incur costs in our fourth quarter related to employee separation benefits, with savings to be realized over the next
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	12-18
</FONT>
	months.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Since December 2015, we have completed five acquisitions, representing in excess of
	$450&nbsp;million in annual sales. Three of the acquisitions were broadline distributors, which have helped further our growth with independent restaurants. The remaining two acquisitions were specialty distributors, which further our penetration in
	the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	center-of-the-plate
</FONT>
</FONT>
</FONT>
	and produce product categories.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We expect continued growth in foodservice industry demand. We expect competitive pressures to remain high. We also expect a continuation of
	the deflationary environment into early 2017. General economic trends and conditions, including demographic changes, inflation, deflation, consumer confidence, and disposable income, coupled with changing tastes and preferences, influence the amount
	that consumers spend on food-away-from-home, which can affect our customers and in turn our sales. Overall, we believe that these general trends will support positive real growth in food-away-from-home consumption and the growth of foodservice
	industry sales.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Sales to our independent restaurant customers, which generally have higher margins, continue to be an increasing
	proportion of our sales mix. Favorable customer mix, additional volume from acquisitions, as well as other merchandising initiatives, have contributed to our ability to expand our margins during a deflationary environment. Additionally, given that a
	large portion of our business is based on markups over cost, sudden inflation or prolonged deflation can negatively impact our sales and gross profit.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Additionally, we believe our investments in a common technology platform, efficient transactional and operational model,
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	e-commerce
</FONT>
	and analytic tools that support our team-based selling approach, coupled with merchandising and product innovation, have helped us leverage our costs, maintain our sales, and differentiate ourselves from
	our competitors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	52
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage60"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D323345DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As of October&nbsp;1, 2016, approximately
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	one-third
</FONT>
	of
	our facilities have employees represented by unions with CBAs. While we believe we generally have good relations with our employees, including those represented by unions, from time to time we experience work stoppages or strikes.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In May 2016, employees represented by the Teamsters Locals 848 and 542 at our Corona, California distribution center went on strike for a
	period of three days, and we reached agreement on a successor CBA in September 2016. In April 2016, the Baltimore employees represented by the Teamsters Locals 570 and 355 went on strike. In June 2016, we ceased operations at our Baltimore, Maryland
	distribution center; and we reached closure agreements with Teamsters Local 570 and Teamsters Local 355 in June 2016 and October 2016, respectively. From time to time, when there are labor-related issues at a facility represented by a Teamsters
	local union, sympathy strikes occur at other facilities that are represented by other Teamsters Local unions. In October 2016, Teamsters Local 455 at our Denver, Colorado distribution center went on strike for a period of three days.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	These labor disruptions did not have a material impact on our business, because of our contingency plans to mitigate any adverse effects of
	such labor disputes and work stoppages. Future labor disruptions and work stoppages may be disruptive to our business and can lead to lower sales and higher operating costs, and could cause customer deliveries to be delayed and our warehouse and
	delivery costs to increase, which could result in a material impact on our business.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Through October 1, 2016, five CBAs covering
	approximately 600 employees were renegotiated. As of October 1, 2016, nine CBAs covering approximately 800 employees were subject to renegotiation during the remainder of fiscal 2016. During fiscal 2017, eight CBAs covering approximately 750
	employees are subject to renegotiation.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We will remain focused on executing our growth strategies, adding value for and differentiating
	ourselves with our customers, and driving continued operational improvement in the business.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	53
</P>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(1)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	EBITDA, Adjusted EBITDA, and Adjusted Net income are
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-GAAP
</FONT>
	measures
	used by management to measure operating performance. EBITDA is defined as Net income (loss), plus Interest expense&#151;net, Income tax provision (benefit), and Depreciation and amortization. Adjusted EBITDA is defined as EBITDA adjusted for 1)
	Sponsor fees; 2) Restructuring and tangible asset impairment charges; 3) Share-based compensation expense; 4) the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-cash
</FONT>
	impact of LIFO reserve adjustments; 5) Loss on extinguishment of debt; 6) Pension
	settlements; 7) Business transformation costs; 8) Acquisition-related costs; 9) Acquisition termination fees&#151;net; and 10) Other gains, losses, or charges as specified in USF&#146;s debt agreements. Adjusted Net income is defined as Net income
	(loss) excluding the items used to calculate Adjusted EBITDA listed above and further adjusted for the tax effect of the exclusions. EBITDA, Adjusted
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	54
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage62"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D323345DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	EBITDA, and Adjusted Net income as presented in this prospectus are supplemental measures of our performance that are not required by&#151;or presented in accordance with&#151;GAAP. They are not
	measurements of our performance under GAAP and should not be considered as alternatives to Net income (loss) or any other performance measures derived in accordance with GAAP.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Free cash flow is defined as Cash flows provided by operating activities less Capital expenditures. Free cash flow is used by management as a
	supplemental measure of our liquidity. We believe that Free cash flow is a useful financial metric to assess our ability to pursue business opportunities and investments. Free cash flow is not a measure of our liquidity under GAAP and should not be
	considered as an alternative to Cash flows provided by operating activities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For additional information, see &#147;Selected Historical
	Consolidated Financial
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Data&#151;Non-GAAP
</FONT>
	Reconciliations.&#148;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Results of Operations
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Accounting Periods
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We operate on a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	52-53&nbsp;week
</FONT>
	fiscal year with all periods ending on a Saturday. When a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	53-week
</FONT>
	fiscal year occurs, we report the additional week in the fourth quarter. Fiscal 2016 is a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	52-week
</FONT>
	fiscal year. Fiscal 2015 was a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	53-week
</FONT>
	fiscal year. Fiscal 2014 and fiscal 2013 were
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	52-week
</FONT>
	fiscal years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended October&nbsp;1, 2016 and September&nbsp;26, 2015
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Highlights
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Case volume increased 2.5%. Independent restaurant case volume increased 6.5%.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Net sales increased $49&nbsp;million, or 0.3%, to $17,241&nbsp;million.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Operating income increased $161&nbsp;million, or 117.5%, to $298&nbsp;million in 2016.&nbsp;As a percentage of Net sales, Operating income increased to 1.7% in 2016, as compared to 0.8% in 2015.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Net income decreased $44&nbsp;million, or 24.9% to $133&nbsp;million. As a percentage of Net sales, Net income decreased to 0.8% in 2016 compared to 1.0% in 2015.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Adjusted EBITDA increased to $707&nbsp;million in 2016 from $620&nbsp;million in 2015.&nbsp;As a percentage of Net sales, Adjusted EBITDA increased to 4.1% in 2016 compared to 3.6% in 2015.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Net Sales
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Total
	case growth of 2.5% reflected growth with independent restaurants, education, and hospitality customers, partially offset by planned exits from national restaurant chains. Total organic case volume increased 1.1%, and reflected similar customer
	growth trends. Independent restaurant case growth was approximately 6.5% over the prior year, with organic independent restaurant growth contributing approximately 4.5%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Net sales increased $49&nbsp;million, or 0.3% to $17,241 in 2016, comprised of a 2.5% increase in case volume, partially offset by a 2.2%
	reduction in the overall rate per case. The increase in case volume improved Net sales by approximately $434&nbsp;million, while the rate per case reduced Net sales by approximately $385&nbsp;million. Acquisitions increased sales by approximately
	$196&nbsp;million or 1.1%. Sales of private brand products represented approximately 33% and 32% of total sales for the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	in 2016 and 2015, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The overall rate per case decline of 2.2% as compared to the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	of 2015 reflects a continuation
	of the deflationary environment and product mix changes. Deflation is estimated to contribute to approximately
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	two-thirds
</FONT>
	of the rate per case decline with mix shifts driving the remainder. Deflation was
	experienced in several commodity categories, but particularly in beef, which contributed to lower average selling prices per case.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	55
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage63"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D323345DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Changes in product costs impact Net sales since a significant portion of our business is based on markups over cost. Product mix changes include impacts from our produce company acquisition.
	Produce, as a category, has lower selling prices per case than our average, which brings down our average selling price per case when these sales are consolidated in our overall results. Mix changes also include the transition away from certain
	national restaurant chain customers whose purchases were concentrated in certain protein categories.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Gross Profit
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Gross profit increased $91&nbsp;million, or 3.1%, to $3,026&nbsp;million in the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	of 2016. As a
	percentage of Net sales, Gross profit increased by 0.5% to 17.6% in 2016 from 17.1% in 2015.&nbsp;Higher case volume, including the impact of acquisitions, increased Gross profit, as a percent of sales, by 0.2%, compared to 2015.&nbsp;Additionally,
	merchandising initiatives, including efforts to reduce product costs through vendor management and other margin improvement initiatives, increased Gross profit, as a percent of sales by 0.4% compared to the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	of 2015.&nbsp;Our LIFO method of inventory costing decreased Gross profit by $17&nbsp;million or 0.1%, as a percent of sales, as compared to 2015. Deflationary trends resulted in a LIFO benefit of
	$25&nbsp;million in 2016 compared to a benefit of $42&nbsp;million in 2015. We experienced deflation in
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	center-of-plate
</FONT>
</FONT>
	items, most notably from beef and dairy.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Distribution, Selling and Administrative Costs
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Distribution, selling and administrative costs decreased $27&nbsp;million, or 1.0%, to $2,689&nbsp;million in 2016. As a percentage of Net
	sales, Distribution, selling and administrative costs decreased 0.2%, to 15.6% in 2016 from 15.8% in 2015. The decrease included $25&nbsp;million of lower distribution expenses, driven by fuel savings, $16&nbsp;million of net reductions in
	postretirement benefit costs, a $14&nbsp;million net benefit related to an improvement in litigation settlements, $10&nbsp;million of favorable self-insurance experience, and $7&nbsp;million of wage benefits resulting from the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-recurrence
</FONT>
	of certain 2015 retention benefits related to the Acquisition. These improvements were partially offset by the $31&nbsp;million termination fee paid to our Sponsors during the second quarter of 2016,
	and a $15&nbsp;million increase in depreciation and amortization expense, primarily related to fleet assets and additional intangible asset amortization.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Restructuring and Tangible Asset Impairment Charges
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Restructuring and tangible asset impairment charges decreased $43&nbsp;million, or 52.4%, to $39&nbsp;million in 2016. During the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended October&nbsp;1, 2016, we recognized $39&nbsp;million of costs comprised of $7&nbsp;million of employee separation costs to centralize field procurement activities and $32&nbsp;million of costs related
	the field reorganization and Baltimore, Maryland distribution center closure.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended September&nbsp;26, 2015, we recognized $82&nbsp;million of costs related to the field reorganization and Baltimore, Maryland distribution center closure. The field reorganization costs of approximately $31&nbsp;million, were primarily
	comprised of employee separation costs. The Baltimore costs of approximately $51&nbsp;million were comprised of $46&nbsp;million for estimated multiemployer pension withdrawal liabilities and $5&nbsp;million related to other employee separation and
	related costs. The estimated multiemployer pension cost was based on the latest available information received from the respective plans&#146; administrator and represented an estimate for a calendar year 2014 withdrawal, which was the most recent
	information available at the time.&nbsp;Due to the lack of current information, including changes in market conditions, and funded status of the related multiemployer pension plans, the settlement of these multiemployer pension withdrawal
	liabilities could materially differ from initial estimates.
</P>
<EFX_OPERATING_EXPENSES>
<A NAME="FIS_OPERATING_EXPENSES"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Operating Expenses
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating expenses, comprised of Distribution, selling, and administrative costs and Restructuring and tangible asset impairment charges,
	decreased $69&nbsp;million, or 2.5% to $2,728&nbsp;million. Operating expenses as a percent of Net sales were 15.8% for the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	of 2016, down from 16.3% in 2015. The change was primarily due to the
	factors discussed in the relevant sections above.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	56
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage64"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D323345DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Operating Income
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income increased $161&nbsp;million, or 117.5%, to $298&nbsp;million in 2016. Operating income as a percentage of Net sales increased
	0.9% to 1.7% for the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	of 2016, up from 0.8% in 2015. The change was primarily due to the factors discussed above.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Acquisition Termination Fees&#151;Net
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	of 2015 included net Acquisition termination fee income of $288&nbsp;million, comprised of
	$300&nbsp;million paid to us in connection with the termination of the Acquisition Agreement offset in part by a $12.5&nbsp;million termination fee paid by us in connection with the termination of the related asset purchase agreement.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Interest Expense&#151;Net
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Interest expense&#151;net was $21&nbsp;million lower primarily due to the pay down and refinancing of debt during the second quarter of 2016.
	See &#147;Description of Certain Indebtedness&#148; and Note 10, Debt, in our unaudited consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Loss on
	Extinguishment of debt
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As discussed in Note 10, Debt, in our unaudited consolidated financial statements, USF incurred a
	$54&nbsp;million loss on extinguishment of debt in 2016. Approximately $42&nbsp;million of the loss related to the June 2016 debt redemption and refinancing. The remaining $12&nbsp;million resulted from the defeasance of the CMBS Fixed Facility. See
	&#147;Description of Certain Indebtedness.&#148;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Income Taxes
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The determination of our overall effective tax rate requires the use of estimates. The effective tax rate reflects the income earned and taxed
	in various United States federal and state jurisdictions based on enacted tax law, permanent differences between book and tax items, tax credits and our change in relative income in each jurisdiction.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We estimated our annual effective tax rate for the full fiscal year and applied the annual effective tax rate to the results of the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended October&nbsp;1, 2016 and September&nbsp;26, 2015 for purposes of determining our
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	year-to-date
</FONT>
</FONT>
	tax provision (benefit).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We released the valuation allowance against our federal net deferred tax assets and certain of our state net deferred tax assets in the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	13-weeks
</FONT>
	ended October&nbsp;1, 2016 as we determined it was more likely than not the deferred tax assets would be realized. We maintained a valuation allowance on certain state net operating loss and tax credit
	carryforwards expected to expire unutilized as a result of insufficient forecasted taxable income in the carryforward period or the utilization of which is subject to limitation. The decision to release the valuation allowance was made after
	management considered all available evidence, both positive and negative, including but not limited to, historical operating results, cumulative income in recent years, forecasted earnings, and a reduction of uncertainty regarding forecasted
	earnings as a result of developments in certain customer and strategic initiatives during the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	13-weeks
</FONT>
	ended October&nbsp;1, 2016
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The effective tax rate for the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended October&nbsp;1, 2016 and September&nbsp;26, 2015 of
	(143)% and 17%, respectively, varied from the 35% federal statutory rate, primarily as a result of a change in the valuation allowance and the recognition of various discrete tax items. During the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended October&nbsp;1, 2016 and September&nbsp;26, 2015, the valuation allowance decreased $101&nbsp;million and $43&nbsp;million, respectively. The decrease in the valuation allowance for the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended
	October&nbsp;1, 2016 was primarily the result of the year to date
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	57
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage65"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D323345DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	ordinary income and the corresponding release of the valuation allowance. The discrete tax items for the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended October&nbsp;1, 2016 included a tax
	benefit of $80&nbsp;million, primarily related to the release of the valuation allowance. The decrease in the valuation allowance for the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended September&nbsp;26, 2015 was primarily the result of the
	year to date ordinary income, partially offset by an increase in the valuation allowance due to an increase in deferred tax liabilities related to indefinite-lived intangibles. The year to date ordinary income for the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended September&nbsp;26, 2015 was impacted by the $288&nbsp;million net termination fee received pursuant to the terminated Acquisition Agreement. The discrete tax items for the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	39-weeks
</FONT>
	ended September&nbsp;26, 2015 included a tax benefit of $2&nbsp;million primarily related to the settlement of tax audits and the expiration of the statute of limitations in various state and local
	jurisdictions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Net Income
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our Net income was $133&nbsp;million in 2016 as compared to $177&nbsp;million in 2015. The decrease in Net income is due to the factors
	discussed above.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Fiscal Years Ended January&nbsp;2, 2016 and December&nbsp;27, 2014
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

	Highlights
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Net sales for fiscal 2015 increased 0.5% to $23,127&nbsp;million as compared to $23,020&nbsp;million in fiscal 2014. Excluding the estimated impact of the 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	week
	in 2015, Net sales decreased by approximately 1.1%.
</TD>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Operating income for fiscal 2015 was $190&nbsp;million. As a percentage of Net sales, Operating income decreased to 0.8% for fiscal 2015, as compared to 1.1% in fiscal 2014. Operating income includes $173&nbsp;million
	of charges incurred related to initiatives designed to optimize our operating model and to reduce our operating cost base.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

	Net income in fiscal 2015 was $168&nbsp;million as compared to a Net loss of $73&nbsp;million in fiscal 2014. Fiscal 2015 includes $288&nbsp;million in net fees received in connection with the termination of the
	Acquisition Agreement and Acquisition related costs of $85&nbsp;million as compared to $38&nbsp;million in fiscal 2014.
</TD>

</TD>

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Fiscal 2015 included 53 weeks while fiscal 2014 included 52 weeks. To enhance comparability, the estimated impact of the 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	week is noted below.
</TD>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Net Sales
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Net
	sales increased $107&nbsp;million, or 0.5%, to $23,127&nbsp;million in 2015 as compared to 2014. Case volume increased 1% in 2015 as compared to 2014. The impact of the 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	week on Net sales was
	estimated to be a 1.5% increase in case volume or approximately $350&nbsp;million. Excluding the estimated impact of the 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	week in 2015, Net sales decreased by 1.1% as a result of a 0.5%
	decline in case volume and a 0.6% reduction in overall price per case. The decline in case volume and price per case decreased Net sales by $106&nbsp;million and $136&nbsp;million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Restaurant case volume changes were relatively consistent with total case volume changes; however, within restaurants we experienced a
	recovery in independent restaurant customer growth as merger uncertainty lifted, which was offset by declines in national restaurant chain customers partly as a result of our exit from serving certain national restaurant chain customers in 2015
	compared to 2014. Independent restaurant customer case growth, excluding the estimated impact of the 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	week in 2015, was 4.0%. Total case volume was negatively impacted by approximately 1.6% as
	a result of no longer serving the previously noted national restaurant chain customers. Sales of private brand products represented approximately 30% of net sales in both 2015 and 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	58
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage66"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D323345DS1A_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The overall price per case decline of 0.6% reflects the deflationary environment in 2015.
	Inflation earlier in 2015 shifted to deflation through much of 2015. Changes in product cost impact Net sales since a significant portion of our business is based on markups over cost.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Gross Profit
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Gross profit increased $215&nbsp;million, or 5.7%, to $4,013&nbsp;million in 2015. As a percentage of Net sales, Gross profit increased by 0.9%
	to 17.4% in 2015 from 16.5% in 2014. Our LIFO inventory costing increased Gross profit by $134&nbsp;million or 3.5% as compared to the prior year. Fiscal 2015 had a LIFO benefit of $74&nbsp;million compared to a LIFO charge of $60&nbsp;million in
	2014, driven by product deflation through much of 2015 compared to inflation in 2014. Product categories experiencing cost inflation in 2015 included beef, while areas of more significant deflation included cheese, pork, and seafood. The impact of
	the 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	week on Gross profit in 2015 was estimated to be an increase of approximately $60&nbsp;million. Excluding the estimated impact of the
	53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	week in 2015, Gross profit increased approximately 4.1%, as compared to 2014. Additionally, merchandising initiatives, including efforts to reduce product costs through vendor management and
	other margin improvement initiatives, increased Gross profit by 1.1% over fiscal 2014 while lower sales volume reduced Gross profit by 0.5%, compared to fiscal 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Distribution, Selling and Administrative Costs
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Distribution, selling and administrative costs increased $104&nbsp;million, or 2.9%, to $3,650&nbsp;million in 2015. As a percentage of Net
	sales, Distribution, selling and administrative costs increased 40 basis points to 15.8% in 2015 from 15.4% in 2014. The increase was due to $47&nbsp;million of higher Acquisition-related costs, a $49&nbsp;million increase in salaries and wages, an
	$11&nbsp;million increase in our pension and other postretirement benefit costs, which were impacted by the 2014 year end
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	re-measurement,
</FONT>
	reflecting lower discount rates, and the 2014 year end mortality table
	updates related to our Company-sponsored benefit plans (see &#147;&#151;Retirement Plans&#148; below), $16&nbsp;million in legal settlement costs, and $16&nbsp;million of brand
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	re-launch
</FONT>
	and related marketing
	costs. These were partially offset by $24&nbsp;million of lower fuel expenses, driven by declining fuel prices, a $12&nbsp;million decrease in depreciation and amortization expense, primarily related to information technology and fleet assets, and a
	net insurance benefit of $11&nbsp;million related to a prior year facility tornado loss. The impact of the 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	week on Distribution, selling and administrative costs is estimated to be
	approximately $50&nbsp;million. Excluding the estimated impact of the 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	week in 2015, Distribution, selling and administrative costs increased approximately 1.5% as compared to 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Restructuring and Tangible Asset Impairment Charges
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During 2015, the following events occurred:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	We reached a settlement with the Central States Teamsters Union Pension Plan (&#147;Central States&#148;). The settlement relieved the Company&#146;s participation in the &#147;legacy&#148; pool and settled the related
	legacy multiemployer pension withdrawal liability, and commenced the Company as a new employer status in the &#147;hybrid&#148; pool of the Central States Teamsters Southeast and Southwest Area Pension Fund (&#147;Central States Plan&#148;). The
	payment also included the settlement of certain other Central States multiemployer pension withdrawal liabilities relating to facilities closed prior to 2015 and the related Eagan Minnesota labor dispute. The settlement resulted in a restructuring
	charge of $88&nbsp;million representing the excess of the $97&nbsp;million cash payment over the aforementioned prior liabilities related to these previously closed facilities.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	We announced our plan to streamline our field operational model. A restructuring charge of $30&nbsp;million was recorded in fiscal 2015 and consisted primarily of employee separation related costs. We anticipate the
	reorganization will be completed in fiscal 2016, and we expect to incur additional charges in fiscal 2016 related to this organizational realignment, which we estimate to be approximately $7&nbsp;million.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;

</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	We announced our tentative decision to close the Baltimore, Maryland distribution center and accrued a $55&nbsp;million charge, including $50&nbsp;million for the estimated multiemployer pension plan withdrawal. A final
	decision to close the Baltimore, Maryland distribution center was announced in April 2016 and the facility was closed in June 2016. In December 2016, we reached agreement with the plan administrators to settle the $50&nbsp;million withdrawal
	liability estimate for $46&nbsp;million. The $46&nbsp;million was paid in December 2016.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Operating Expenses
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating expenses, comprised of Distribution, selling, and administrative costs and Restructuring and tangible asset impairment
	charges, increased $277&nbsp;million, or 7.8% to $3,823&nbsp;million. Operating expenses as a percent of Net sales were 16.5% in 2015, up from 15.4% in 2014. The change was primarily due to the factors discussed in the relevant sections above.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Operating Income
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income decreased $62&nbsp;million, or 24.6%, to $190&nbsp;million in 2015. Operating income as a percent of Net sales decreased 0.3%
	to 0.8% for 2015, down from 1.1% in 2014. The change was primarily due to the factors discussed above.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Acquisition Termination
	Fees&#151;Net
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Fiscal 2015 included net Acquisition termination fee income of $288&nbsp;million, comprised of $300&nbsp;million
	paid to us in connection with the termination of the Acquisition Agreement offset in part by a $12.5&nbsp;million termination fee paid by us in connection with the termination of the related asset purchase agreement.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Interest Expense&#151;Net
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Interest expense&#151;net decreased $4&nbsp;million to $285&nbsp;million in 2015. The decrease related primarily to certain deferred financing
	fees associated with our 2007 acquisition being fully amortized during the second quarter of 2015, partially offset by approximately $5&nbsp;million of additional interest expense due to the 53
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	rd
</SUP>
	week.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Income Taxes
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We recorded Income tax provisions of $25&nbsp;million and $36&nbsp;million for 2015 and 2014, respectively. The effective tax rate of 13% for
	2015 was primarily affected by a $48&nbsp;million decrease in the valuation allowance and deferred tax liabilities related to indefinite-lived intangibles, which are generally not considered a source of support for realization of the net deferred
	tax asset. The effective tax rate of 97% for 2014 was primarily affected by a $55&nbsp;million increase in the valuation allowance and deferred tax liabilities related to indefinite-lived intangibles and an $8&nbsp;million increase in deferred tax
	assets related to additional income tax credits. The difference between the $48&nbsp;million decrease in the valuation allowance and deferred tax liabilities related to indefinite-lived intangibles in 2015 as compared to an increase of
	$55&nbsp;million in 2014 was primarily the result of income received in connection with the Acquisition Agreement termination fee in 2015 and an increase in valuation allowance related to the increase in deferred tax assets for additional income tax
	credits in 2014. See Note 20, Income Taxes, in our audited consolidated financial statements for a reconciliation of our effective tax rates to the statutory rate.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Net Income (Loss)
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our Net income was $168&nbsp;million in 2015 as compared to a Net loss of $73&nbsp;million in 2014. The increase in Net income is due to the
	factors discussed above.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;

	60

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Net sales increased $723&nbsp;million in 2014, or 3.2%, to $23,020&nbsp;million.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Operating income, as a percentage of Net sales, was 1.1% in 2014 as compared to 1.4% in 2013.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Net loss was $73&nbsp;million in 2014 as compared to a Net loss of $57&nbsp;million in 2013 and reflects an increase of $34&nbsp;million in Acquisition-related costs.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Adjusted EBITDA increased 2.5%, or $21&nbsp;million, to $866&nbsp;million.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Net Sales
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Net sales increased $723&nbsp;million, or 3.2%, to $23,020&nbsp;million in 2014 as compared to $22,297&nbsp;million in 2013.
	Although case volume declined 1.2% or approximately $275&nbsp;million, product cost inflation resulted in an overall price per case increase of 4.5%, increasing Net sales by approximately $998&nbsp;million because a significant portion of our
	business is based on markups over cost. The increase in sales was partially offset by the impact of competitive market conditions and lower case volume. Restaurant volume was the primary driver of a decrease in total cases as a result of our exit
	from serving certain national restaurant chain customers and represented a 1.4% case volume decrease compared to the prior year. Sales of private brand products were approximately 30% of our Net sales in fiscal 2014, representing approximately a 90
	basis points increase as compared to 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Gross Profit
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Gross profit decreased $25&nbsp;million, or 0.6%, to $3,798&nbsp;million in 2014 from $3,823&nbsp;million in 2013. As a percentage of Net
	sales, Gross profit decreased by 0.6% to 16.5% in 2014 from 17.1% in 2013. Our LIFO inventory costing decreased Gross profit by 1.3% or approximately $48&nbsp;million as compared to the prior year due to higher product cost inflation in 2014. In
	addition to the impact of LIFO, lower sales volume reduced gross profit by 1.3%, compared to 2013. Continued competitive market conditions also impacted our ability to pass along year over year product inflation, negatively impacting year over year
	gross profit. Significant product categories experiencing higher inflation included several
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	center-of-plate
</FONT>
</FONT>
	products, and cheese and dairy. Merchandising initiatives,
	including efforts to reduce product costs through vendor management and other margin improvement initiatives partially offset by the impact of higher product costs resulted in a 2.1% increase to Gross profit compared to 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Distribution, Selling and Administrative Costs
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Distribution, selling and administrative expenses increased $52&nbsp;million, or 1.5%, to $3,546&nbsp;million in 2014 from $3,494&nbsp;million
	in 2013. As a percentage of Net sales, Distribution, selling and administrative costs decreased by 30 basis points to 15.4% in 2014 from 15.7% in 2013. The 2014 increase was due primarily to $38&nbsp;million of costs related to the terminated
	Acquisition Agreement, and a $24&nbsp;million increase in depreciation and amortization expense, primarily due to technology and fleet investments. These increases were partially offset by a $9&nbsp;million decrease in marketing and branding-related
	costs. Year over year wage inflation increases were offset by lower headcount and a $20&nbsp;million decrease in pension and other postretirement benefit costs related to our Company-sponsored benefit plans.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Restructuring and Tangible Asset Impairment Charges
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Restructuring and tangible asset impairment charges were immaterial in 2014. During 2013, we recognized Restructuring and tangible asset
	impairment charges of $8&nbsp;million mainly attributable to the decision to close three distribution centers that ceased operating in 2014, resulting in $4&nbsp;million of severance and related costs. The remainder was attributable to impairment
	charges related to the adjustment to estimated fair value, less costs to sell, of certain Assets held for sale and other severance costs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	61
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Operating Expenses
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating expenses, comprised of Distribution, selling, and administrative costs and Restructuring and tangible asset impairment charges,
	increased $44&nbsp;million, or 1.3%, to $3,546&nbsp;million. Operating expenses as a percent of Net sales were 15.4% in 2014, down from 15.7% in 2013. The change was primarily due to the factors discussed in the relevant sections above.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Operating Income
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income decreased $69&nbsp;million, or 21.5%, to $252&nbsp;million in 2014. Operating income as a percent of Net sales decreased 0.3%
	to 1.1% for 2014, down from 1.4% in 2013. The change was primarily due to the factors discussed above.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Interest
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	Expense-Net
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Interest expense&#151;Net decreased $17&nbsp;million to $289&nbsp;million in 2014
	from $306&nbsp;million in 2013. Lower overall borrowing costs as a result of the 2013 debt refinancing transactions and a decrease in average borrowings on our revolving credit facility were partially offset by higher interest expense attributable
	to capital lease additions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Loss on Extinguishment of Debt
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The 2013 Loss on extinguishment of debt consists of a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	write-off
</FONT>
	of unamortized debt issuance costs, as
	well as loan fees and third party costs relating to the Amended 2011 Term Loan, and an early redemption premium and a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	write-off
</FONT>
	of unamortized debt issuance costs relating to the redemption of our 11.25%
	Senior Subordinated Notes due 2017 (the &#147;Senior Subordinated Notes&#148;).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Income Taxes
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We recorded Income tax provisions of $36&nbsp;million and $30&nbsp;million for 2014 and 2013, respectively. The effective tax rate of 97% for
	2014 was primarily affected by a $55&nbsp;million increase in the valuation allowance and deferred tax liabilities related to indefinite-lived intangibles and an $8&nbsp;million increase in deferred tax assets related to additional income tax
	credits. The effective tax rate of 109% for 2013 was primarily affected by a $32&nbsp;million increase in the valuation allowance and deferred tax liabilities related to indefinite-lived intangibles and a $5&nbsp;million decrease in deferred tax
	assets for stock awards settled. The difference between the $55&nbsp;million increase in the valuation allowance and deferred tax liabilities related to indefinite-lived intangibles in 2014 as compared to an increase of $32&nbsp;million in 2013 was
	primarily the result of additional valuation allowance related to the increase in deferred tax assets for additional income tax credits in 2014, less valuation allowance for the decrease in deferred tax assets for stock awards settled in 2013, and a
	tax benefit recognized in continuing operations due to the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	year-to-date
</FONT>
</FONT>
	gain in Other comprehensive income in 2013. See Note 20, Income Taxes, in our audited
	consolidated financial statements for a reconciliation of our effective tax rates to the statutory rate.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:2%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Net Loss
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our Net loss was $73&nbsp;million in 2014 as compared to a Net loss of $57&nbsp;million in 2013. The decrease in Net loss is due to the factors
	discussed above.
</P>
